                    <msContents>
                        <summary> A work on Obstetrics by Katakura Kakuryō. It draws on both Dutch and English works, most probably via Dutch translations, reproducing some of the original illustrations, describing difficult births and how they should be managed. It is written in Kanbun so likely intended as a scholarly text. The work was first published in 1799, but minor additions were made to the blocks in 1803 and 1822; this copy dates from 1822 or shortly thereafter. </summary>

                        <textLang mainLang="ja" source="IANA">Japanese</textLang>

                        <msItem n="1" xml:id="Japanese_68">

                            <author key="person_ 256535858" source="VIAF">
                                <persName type="original" xml:lang="ja">片倉鶴陵</persName>
                                <persName type="standard" xml:lang="ja-Latn">Katakura Kakuryō</persName>
                                <note><p>Katakura Kakuryō (1751-1822) was adopted into a medical
                                        family at a young age and later studied with the Taki family
                                        in Edo, who served the Bakufu government as doctors.
                                        Subsequently he studied with Kagawa Gen’etsu in Kyoto, a
                                        pioneer in Obstetrics, and was one of the first to explain
                                        the uses and functions of forceps in Japan. He wrote many
                                        books on medicine and his fame was such that he was even
                                        called in to assist with a difficult birth in the Shogun’s
                                        household, even though he had no official
                                    standing.</p></note>
                            </author>

                            <respStmt>
                                <persName type="original" xml:lang="ja">須原屋茂兵衛</persName>
